{"title_page": "Shekha of Amarsar", "text_new": "[[File:Maharao shekha - Copy.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha]][[File:Maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha statue at village ralawata near jeenmata, district sikar, Rajasthan india]]{{One source|date=April 2020}}\n'''MahaRao Shekha''' (1433\u20131488), was a chieftain in 15th-century India. The [[Shekhawati]] gets its name from him, comprising the districts of [[Sikar district|Sikar]], [[Churu district|Churu]] and [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] in the present-day Indian state of [[Rajasthan]]. The descendants of him known as the \"Shekhawat\".\n\n==Birth==\nHe was born to the [[Kachwaha]] chief Mokul singh. His parents, previously childless, are said to have sought the religious intercession of the Muslim [[Pir (Sufism)|pir]] Shaikh Burhan, for whom Shekha was named. In due time shaikh burhan had an heir,who according to the injunctions of boorhan, was styled after his own tribe,Shekh. He directed that child should wear the buddea(a strings or threads) which, when laid aside , was to be suspended at the saint's [[Dargah|durgah]]; and further ,that he should assume the blue [[tunic]] and [[cap]], abstain from [[Pig|hog]]'s flesh and eat no meat\"in which the blood remained.\" He also ordained that at the birth of every Shekhawat male infant a goat should be sacrificed. These obligations religiously maintained by a couple of centuries. <ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=359[https://archive.org/details/annalsandantiqu00todgoog/page/n359]}}</ref></br>\n\n==Life==\nMaharao Shekha, when he attained man's estate, greatly augmented the territory left by his father, and consolidated 360 villages under his sway,by conquest from his neighbours, when his reputation and power attracted the jealous notice of the lord paramount of amber. He was attached, but by the aid of the Punnee Pathans he successfully withstood the reiterated assaults of his suzerain. Up to this period they had acknowledged the amber prices as liege lords, and in token of alliance paid as tribute all the colts reared on the original estate. A dispute on this point was the ostensible cause(though subordinate to their rapid prosperity), which occasioned a total separation of the Shekhawat colonies from the parent state, until the reign of Sawai Jay Singh, submission and pecuniary relief from them. Shekha left a well-established authority to his youngest son Raimal.<ref name=\":04\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=360[https://archive.org/details/annalsandantiqu00todgoog/page/n360]}}</ref></br>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of Rajasthan]]\n*[[Rajput]]\n*[[Rajputana]]\n*[[Shekhawati]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shekha Of Amarsar}}\n[[Category:15th-century Indian monarchs]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Maharao shekha - Copy.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha]][[File:Maharao shekha statue.jpg|thumb|Maharao Shekha statue at village ralawata near jeenmata, district sikar, Rajasthan india]]{{One source|date=April 2020}}\n'''MahaRao Shekha''' (1433\u20131488), was a chieftain in 15th-century India. The [[Shekhawati]] gets its name from him, comprising the districts of [[Sikar district|Sikar]], [[Churu district|Churu]] and [[Jhunjhunu district|Jhunjhunu]] in the present-day Indian state of [[Rajasthan]]. The descendants of him known as the \"Shekhawat\".\n\nHe was born to the [[Kachwaha]] chief Mokul singh. His parents, previously childless, are said to have sought the religious intercession of the Muslim [[Pir (Sufism)|pir]] Shaikh Burhan, for whom Shekha was named.</br>\n\nIn due time shaikh burhan had an heir,who according to the injunctions of boorhan, was styled after his own tribe,Shekh. He directed that child should wear the buddea(a strings or threads) which, when laid aside , was to be suspended at the saint's [[Dargah|durgah]]; and further ,that he should assume the blue [[tunic]] and [[cap]], abstain from [[Pig|hog]]'s flesh and eat no meat\"in which the blood remained.\" He also ordained that at the birth of every Shekhawat male infant a goat should be sacrificed. These obligations religiously maintained by a couple of centuries. <ref name=\":03\">{{Cite book|last=James tod|first=|url=http://ndl.iitkgp.ac.in/document/eXlWV2YwcUJjMmk5NStkV1dBOWlUVmtoM2tNa2hCUFBxMlo0MGd1QzRiND0|title=Annals & Antiquities of Rajasthan or the central & western Rajput states of India|date=1873|publisher= madras Higginbotham and co 165 mount road|year=1873|isbn=|location=|page=359[https://archive.org/details/annalsandantiqu00todgoog/page/n359]}}</ref></br>\n\n==Life==\nMaharao Shekha, when he attained man's estate, greatly augmented the territory left by his father, and consolidated 360 villages under his sway,by conquest from his neighbours, when his reputation and power attracted the jealous notice of the lord paramount of amber. He was attached, but by the aid of the Punnee Pathans he successfully withstood the reiterated assaults of his suzerain. Up to this period they had acknowledged the amber prices as liege lords, and in token of alliance paid as tribute all the colts reared on the original estate. A dispute on this point was the ostensible cause(though subordinate to their rapid prosperity), which occasioned a total separation of the Shekhawat colonies from the parent state, until the reign of Sawai Jay Singh, submission and pecuniary relief from them. Shekha left a well-established authority to his youngest son Raimal.<re